Crossposted-To: comp.os.linux.help
From: becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker)
Subject: Re: [Q] 3c503: Configured interrupt number 15 is out of range.
Date: Tue, 7 Sep 1993 21:13:08 GMT

In article <268esh$4f5@news.u.washington.edu> roland@cac.washington.edu (Liem Bahneman) writes:
>I've recently gotten a 3comm Etherlink II ethernet card, but only the
>original mcc (pl10+) bootimage seems to detect it. I've recompiled pl12 4
>times and still cannot get it to even probe for it. (I've copiled in ALL
>ethernet card drivers). How do I get pl12 to probe for a 3c503?

First of all, you'll probably want to change your 3c503 to use shared
memory.  The jumper is shared with the boot PROM, so you may have
missed it.

What does this have to do with the 3c503 probe?  Well, the probe for
a 3c503 in programmed-I/O mode was turned off in a panic reaction to
the general device driver probe explosion.  (The 3c503 shared memory
probe is a safe read from memory, rather than a scan through I/O
space.)  The new pl13 kernel has a I/O port registrar that makes I/O
space probes safer, and the programmed-I/O 3c503 probe has been
re-enabled.   You still shouldn't use the programmed-I/O mode though,
it's noticeably slower.  It's there only for compatibility (long story
omitted). 

>When I do use the MCC bootimage, it probes for the card, finds it, but
>gives me this error:
>
>3c503: Configured interrupt number 15 is out of range.

This means the MCC people fixed the ethercard IRQ at 15 when they made
the kernel -- a truly evil thing.  The 3c503 can only use IRQ{5, 2/9, 3, 4,}. 
The autoIRQ code should work with everything but the non-EEPROM 80*3.

-- 

Donald Becker                                          becker@super.org
IDA Supercomputing Research Center
17100 Science Drive, Bowie MD 20715                        301-805-7482

