From: urlichs@smurf.sub.org (Matthias Urlichs)
Subject: Re: "Spying" on ttyS0
Date: 6 Sep 1993 11:26:49 +0200

In comp.os.linux.misc, article <STEVEV.93Aug27224526@miser.uoregon.edu>,
  stevev@miser.uoregon.edu (Steve VanDevender) writes:
> In article <25bqu5INN6d4@uwm.edu> zak@csd4.csd.uwm.edu
> (Zachary S Smith) writes:
> 
>    I run a dial-in system, and most of my users are new to unix.  Is there any
>    way I can assign, say, tty8 to look like the remote user's screen?  I just
>    need a way to see if they are floundering, so I can give them a hand.
> 
> The TTY driver doesn't even try to keep track of the state of the
> user's screen.  The best you can do is monitor their current
> input and output.  You can't hope to see exactly what they are
> seeing at the moment.

The best thing you can do is to give them "screen" as their login shell.

Screen is able to give you multiuser terminals (aka "spying" or "giving
users a hand" :-), map terminal types, have multiple virtual terminals,
among others.

The only thing you need will be more swap space because users tend to
leave their screen sessions logged in as soon as they figure out the
heap of neat things screen can do for them. ;-)

