From: iwj10@cus.cam.ac.uk (Ian Jackson)
Subject: Re: SLS considered harmful (wasRe: Bashing Peter MacDonald)
Date: Tue, 7 Sep 1993 19:54:33 GMT

In article <1993Sep4.005345.23721@inca.comlab.ox.ac.uk>,
Stephen Harris <harris@teaching.physics.ox.ac.uk> wrote:
>The whole point of this posting:  the work done by Peter, Le Blanc et al
>is great.  If you don't like it, DON'T USE IT!

There is something of a fallacy here.  You seem to be arguing that
because when something is free you shouldn't demand to have exactly
what you want (true) therefore whatever you're provided with must be
good (false).

The whole problem, as those of us that dislike SLS see it, is that SLS
is *not* great.  If it were great I wouldn't end up cursing every time
I have to work with it.  I often have no control over what is
installed by someone I go and help with their Linux system, and I
certainly have no control over what people install before they post
about their problems to comp.os.linux.help.

Note that I'm not demanding that Peter produce something better.
However I am saying that the kind of `blind gratitude' mentality is
unlikely to produce better results in the future.  I'm glad to see the
appearance on the scene of the new Debian release, under construction.

In the meantime I will continue to recommend in the strongest possible
terms that anybody considering using SLS install MCC instead and untar
the X tree on top of it themselves - it will be easier, and the result
will be better.
