From: jim@n5ial.mythical.com (Jim Graham)
Subject: SIGSEGVs, FS reliability, kernel/fs version ... connection?
Date: Wed, 8 Sep 1993 04:13:01 GMT

Until recently, I was running 0.99 PL6 and was using the minix filesystem.
Some of y'all may recall a post a while back about problems I was having
with regular files suddenly becoming directories (or so the FS thought),
data being trashed, and so on.  When I upgraded to 0.99 PL9 and started
using the ext2 filesystem instead, these problems completely vanished.  I
can now compile the kernel without a single SIGSEGV (I did have one
seg-fault/core dump, but I suspect that was caused by something else).
Before, I often had to re-start the compile on a new kernel at least 5 or
6 times....

I'm pretty sure it isn't the filesystem version, because someone recently
posted about how they were having the same problems, but with the ext2 fs.
I'm also pretty sure it isn't the kernel, because this same person was
using 0.99 PL12, so you'd think if it went away in PL9, it wouldn't be too
likely to suddenly reappear in PL12 (though I do seem to recall having a
SIGSEGV-free OS when I was on some patchlevel of 0.98).

The only other thing I changed when I made that conversion (which, as I
said, is when the problems went away) was the filesystem structure.  I
moved the news spool (/usr/spool/news) to its own partition (/newsspool)
and let a symbolic link point to it.

Does anyone have any idea what could be going on here?  I can see how moving
the news spool off to its own partition could help reduce the filesystem
corruption...after all, if it's the partition that's getting the cr*p beaten
out of it every day, it's the most likely to see a failure.  Btw, I should
mention here that I've stopped seeing errors in my news spool dirs, too....
Anyways, what I can't see is how this would eliminate (not reduce,
eliminate) the SIGSEGV problems.

Anyone have any thoughts on this?  Thanks,
   --jim

